{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2024-08-29T11:44:13.798056+00:00", "modified": "2025-02-06T21:03:58.656827+00:00", "id": 13473407, "conceptrecid": "13473406", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13473407", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.13473406", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.13473407", "metadata": {"title": "Oscar de Beaux : a noteworthy Italian mammalogist and conservationist", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13473407", "publication_date": "2006", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) The history of Italian mammalogy has received so far scanty attention by the scientific community. In the present paper, an homage to Oscar de Beaux is presented 50 years after his death. His scientific activity was characterised by a broad approach to the study of mammals, both in museums and zoos, that was not limited to taxonomy but also included embryology, primatology and conservation. In this latter field, well in advance of his time, de Beaux recognised the strong link existing between taxonomy and conservation 60 years before the Convention on biological diversity being signed in Rio de Janeiro. In his booklet 'Biological Ethics. An attempt to arouse a naturalistic conscience' of 1930, rightly recognised as one of the first works on the ethical aspects of conservation, he also stressed the now widely understood role of naturalistic museums, zoos and botanical gardens as centres of environmental education and awareness. Therefore, de Beaux's work represents not only an important witness of Italian mammalogy, but also a precious heritage for the international scientific community. We hope this paper could help broaden the knowledge of this important scientist in Italy and abroad.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Gippoliti, Spartaco", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/29270f74adbaa7d27a93e325bfb26520", "r